===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

{{wikipedia|Adverb}}
# {{lb|en|grammar}} A [[word]] that [[modify|modifies]] a [[verb]], [[adjective]], other adverbs, or various other types of words, [[phrases]], or [[clause]]s.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1897|author=Henry James|title=What Maisie Knew|passage=‘Fortunately your papa appreciates it; he appreciates it ''immensely''’—that was one of the things Miss Overmore also said, with a striking insistence on the '''adverb'''.}}
#: (''modifying a verb'') {{ux|en|I '''often''' went outside hiking during my stay in Japan.}}
#: (''modifying an adjective'') {{ux|en|It was '''often''' [[cold]] outside.}}
#: (''modifying another adverb'') {{ux|en|Not '''often'''.}}
# {{lb|en|programming}} In the [[Raku]] [[programming language]], a [[named]] [[parameter]] that modifies the behavior of a [[routine]].

====Usage notes====
Adverbs comprise a fundamental category of words in most languages. In English, adverbs are typically formed from adjectives by appending {{m|en|-ly}} and are used to modify verbs, [[verb phrase]]s, adjectives, other adverbs, and entire sentences, but rarely [[noun]]s or [[noun phrase]]s.

